# Global Instructions (template)

Private, always-loaded rules for every Claude Code session. This is the "constitution" —
specifics about *who you are* and *how you work* live in the layered memory system below.
Replace the `<PLACEHOLDERS>` and delete what doesn't apply.

## Memory system (how it's wired) — three tiers, right context at the right time

Persistent memory: `<MEMORY_DIR>` (e.g. `~/.claude/projects/<your-id>/memory/`)

- **Tier 1 — `MEMORY.md`:** the always-in-context index, **hard cap it** (pick a line limit that
  fits your usage, e.g. 40-200 lines). Only what every session needs: who you are, standing
  how-you-work rules, one line per active project, and a pointer to the archive tier. Before
  adding a line, ask "does every future session need this?" — if not, it belongs in a lower tier.
- **Tier 2 — project-local:** facts about a specific project live in *that project's own*
  `CLAUDE.md`, under a `## Session memory` section. It auto-loads only when you're working in
  that project (and is visible to any subagent told to read the project's `CLAUDE.md` first —
  see index-first exploration below). New project-specific learnings go HERE, not into a new
  global memory file.
- **Tier 3 — `ARCHIVE.md`:** an index of dormant projects, killed ideas, and rare references;
  never auto-loaded, only opened when the topic resurfaces. Memory files themselves are never
  deleted, just de-indexed out of Tier 1.
- **Memory files** — one fact per file, typed via frontmatter `metadata.type`:
  - `user` — who you are (role, expertise, preferences)
  - `feedback` — corrections/guidance on how Claude should work (include the *why* + *how to apply*)
  - `project` — ongoing work, goals, constraints not derivable from code/git
  - `reference` — pointers to external resources (URLs, dashboards, API endpoints)
  A file growing past a few KB is becoming a log — distill it, or move the detail project-local.
- **Conversation log** — `conversations_index.md` (one line per past session) + `conversations/`
  (full logs, kept short). Scanned only when prior work is referenced; never bulk-loaded.

Rules: "remember this" → save immediately to the right TIER. Never duplicate — update existing
entries. Absolute dates only (e.g. `2026-06-18`, never "today"). Store *why*, not *what* — never
store code patterns, git history, or anything discoverable by reading the project.

## Model efficiency

Delegate everything that doesn't need top-tier reasoning to the cheapest capable subagent.
Three mechanical rules — mechanical because prose rules get silently ignored under time
pressure, and the failure mode (an expensive model quietly doing cheap work) is easy to fall
into by default:

1. **Every subagent call states its model explicitly.** An unspecified model can inherit your
   most expensive tier by default — check your harness's actual behavior, since a session that
   fans out several subagents without pinning a cheaper model can spend far more than intended.
   Never point a subagent at your most expensive/top-tier model — if a task needs that much
   reasoning, do it in the main loop instead.
2. **The cheapest tier is the DEFAULT delegate for read-shaped work:** searching more than a
   couple of files, unknown locations, extract/filter/summarize from files/logs/output,
   mechanical bulk edits, file census. Reserve the mid tier for code-shaped work: real code,
   fixes/refactors/tests/configs, multi-file synthesis that needs judgment. Escalate from the
   cheap tier to the mid tier only on a verified failure, not by reflex — it's easy to default
   to the mid tier out of habit even when the cheap tier would have done the job for a fraction
   of the cost.
3. **No bulk reading in the main loop** — a context-firewall hook (see `hooks/context-firewall.py`)
   nudges you when it happens. A couple of quick targeted reads inline are fine; a pattern of
   repeated same-shape reads means delegate instead.

Reserve the top tier for: ambiguous/strategic questions, architecture & tradeoff decisions,
complex multi-system debugging, and reviewing what a subagent produced. Run subagents in the
background/in parallel by default — don't block on each one.

## Token economy (value per token)

Biggest levers, in order:

- **Context firewall.** Every top-tier turn re-bills the whole conversation, so a bulk read is
  paid on every later turn, not once. Don't read large files/directories directly into the main
  context — delegate bulk reading/searching to a cheaper subagent that returns a distilled
  *conclusion*, not a file dump.
- **Cache discipline.** Prompt cache TTL is short (minutes, not hours). Batch independent tool
  calls into one turn; don't bloat always-loaded files mid-session or trigger denied-retry loops
  — each cache miss re-bills the whole prefix.
- **Cheap-first escalation.** Default to the cheapest plausible model and let the top tier
  *review*; only redo on verified failure.
- **Verify by stakes.** Cheap adversarial verifiers prevent expensive re-work — scale intensity
  to the stakes (heavier verification on math/money-adjacent code, none on a comment fix).
- **Measure.** A SessionEnd hook appends usage to a token ledger; review it (`/tokens`) and tune
  from data instead of guessing.

## Index-first exploration

Read the project's `CLAUDE.md` and target files directly before spawning agents. When
delegating, tell the subagent to read the project's `CLAUDE.md` first — it cuts token usage
substantially by avoiding redundant re-exploration.

## Hub mode (one front door) — optional

An interactive session started in `~` (not a project dir) **is the hub** — mission control
for everything. First action: read `~/.claude/commands/hub.md` and run that protocol: board
greeting → triage every pasted item (inline vs. background worker with an explicit cheap
model) → verify → act within your own limits for what needs a check-in first →
board/memory/log bookkeeping automatically → hygiene autopilot (recognize the right
`/log`/`/compact`/`/clear` moment from your own history) → ledger autopilot (daily spend
pulse, unprompted improvement suggestions). Escape hatch: a message starting `inline:` stays
in this chat. Hub mode does NOT apply to sessions started inside project dirs,
headless/scheduled runs (their prompts win), or separately-owned sessions. `/hub` arms it
anywhere. Board: `~/.claude/hub/board.md` — the chat is disposable, the disk is durable. See
`commands/hub.md` and the "One-Chat Hub" section of the README for the full pattern.

## Workflow discipline

- Use plan mode for non-trivial or multi-step work; confirm the approach before large or
  hard-to-reverse changes.
- Every project should have a `CLAUDE.md` at its root (file map, architecture, entry points,
  tech stack). If you touch a project that lacks one, create it (`/index`).
- Self-improvement: when you're corrected, capture it as a `feedback` memory so it persists.

## Security

- Review code/dependencies before installing or running them.
- Secrets live in `.env` files and are never committed or echoed into chat, logs, or memory.
- Confirm before outward-facing or hard-to-reverse actions.
